Determining workflow recommendations
I’ve confirmed NOMAD supports both API and App plugin entry points, which changes the recommendation: the best setup is not “plugin or app template” as a single choice, but a split architecture with a standalone app now and a thin NOMAD plugin later.

Reviewed apps.py and models.py, clarified file linking requirements
The best workflow for your stated goal is:

Keep planes as a standalone full-stack product for now, and add a separate thin NOMAD integration plugin later.

That is the highest-flexibility path. Starting from the NOMAD plugin template alone would optimize for integration too early and slow down the part you care about most right now: fast GUI iteration, mocked services, isolated DB resets, and decoupled frontend/backend work. Your current planes stack already gives you that. The plugin template is still useful, but as a second package, not as the main product shell.

Why this is the better split

planes is already a complete app: its own React frontend, FastAPI backend, PostgreSQL, Docker composition, and test surface.
NOMAD plugins are Python packages loaded into NOMAD through entry points. NOMAD does support app-like and API plugin entry points, but those are still integration surfaces inside the NOMAD runtime, not a replacement for an independently evolving full-stack app. You can see NOMAD loading API plugins in main.py and app entry points being collected in apps.py. The entry point types themselves are defined in plugins.py.
If you force Planes into a plugin shape now, you will likely sacrifice exactly the things you want: independent frontend dev server, mock auth, mock DBs, isolated migrations, and faster UI experimentation.
Recommended architecture

Use two packages:

planes
This remains your primary application during development.
It owns:

React GUI
FastAPI backend
mocked or real PostgreSQL
optional mock NOMAD adapter
standalone Docker and tests
packages/nomad-planes-plugin
This is a small integration layer built from the NOMAD plugin template.
It owns:

API entry points into NOMAD
optional app entry point metadata for discovery/navigation
auth/session bridging
NOMAD-side proxying or launch metadata
schema/search integration glue
later embedding hooks for the GUI
That split gives you clean separation:

product code in planes
integration code in the NOMAD plugin
This is better than trying to make planes itself “the plugin”, unless you already know you want to give up standalone deployment.

Practical workflow

Phase 1: Build fast in standalone mode
Keep planes as the main dev target.

Add these capabilities there:

AUTH_MODE=mock|standalone|nomad
DATA_MODE=mock|local|nomad
mock adapters for NOMAD entries/schemas/users
fixture seed commands for DB reset and demo data
frontend feature flags for mocked backend and mocked auth
contract tests against a stable internal adapter interface
At this stage, your frontend should never depend directly on NOMAD-specific URLs or payload quirks. It should talk only to the Planes backend.

Phase 2: Define strict integration seams
Inside Planes, isolate all NOMAD coupling behind adapters.

Recommended seams:

auth_provider
schema_provider
entry_provider
user_provider
search_provider
Each seam should have at least two implementations:

mock
nomad
That is the main design decision that preserves future flexibility. If you do this well, later integration becomes mostly adapter work, not a rewrite.

Phase 3: Add a NOMAD plugin as a bridge
Create a separate plugin package from the NOMAD plugin template.

That plugin should do only NOMAD-specific work:

register API endpoints in NOMAD
expose app metadata if useful
translate NOMAD auth/session into something Planes understands
proxy or federate selected data into Planes
optionally expose a URL inside NOMAD pointing to the Planes GUI
This bridge can remain thin for a long time.

Phase 4: Integrate the GUI gradually
You do not need to fully “move” the GUI into NOMAD immediately.

Use this progression:

External standalone GUI with NOMAD SSO
Link from NOMAD into Planes
Reverse-proxy Planes under a NOMAD path
Optionally embed parts later as a micro-frontend or app plugin
That sequence keeps risk low.

What I would change in Planes now

These are the highest-value changes to make immediately:

Introduce a backend service layer instead of letting route handlers call DB or NOMAD code directly.
Add provider interfaces:
AuthProvider
DatasetProvider
SchemaProvider
SearchProvider
Keep all NOMAD-specific DTO mapping in one module tree, not spread through the app.
Make frontend authentication pluggable:
local dev login
mock login
bearer token passthrough from NOMAD
Keep the frontend talking only to the Planes backend, never directly to NOMAD APIs during normal app flow.
Make URL base paths configurable from day one:
root /
proxied /planes/
embedded mode if needed later
Make CORS, cookie, and token transport mode configurable:
header bearer
cookie passthrough
dev mock token
Add deterministic seed/reset commands for local DB and mock state.
Define a versioned internal API contract between frontend and backend.
Those changes matter more than choosing the perfect template.

Should you use different software packages in Docker now?

Yes, but selectively. The goal is not to replace your stack, only to reduce future friction.

Keep

FastAPI
React
Docker Compose
PostgreSQL for standalone product data
Those are good choices for fast product iteration.

Consider adding

Mock Service Worker in the frontend for realistic API mocking during GUI work
WireMock or a lightweight mock API container only if you need external-service simulation beyond your FastAPI mocks
Traefik or a single reverse proxy strategy that can support both standalone and proxied /planes/ deployment
Redis only if you later need shared cache/session/event bridging
Keycloak test realm import for reproducible auth integration tests
Do not switch to Mongo just to match NOMAD
That would be premature. Use PostgreSQL in Planes if it fits your app model. Integration with NOMAD should happen at the API and auth boundary, not by forcing storage convergence early.

Do not collapse frontend into NOMAD’s GUI build yet
That would slow you down immediately and buy you little today. Instead, make the frontend embeddable later:

configurable base path
no hardcoded absolute URLs
no assumptions about owning the whole browser history
optional shell mode for iframe/proxy embedding
Decision

For your case, the best starting point is:

keep the full-stack app template in planes
do not start with only the NOMAD plugin template
later add a small dedicated NOMAD plugin package as the bridge
So the answer is: use the app template as the product, and the plugin template as the integration layer.

That is the best workflow if your priorities are:

maximum development speed now
independent testing and mocking
minimal lock-in to NOMAD internals
clean later integration into NOMAD
A concrete target structure would be:

planes
packages/nomad-planes-plugin
Where:

planes is the app
nomad-planes-plugin is the connector
If you want, I can next turn this into a concrete repository blueprint: package layout, interfaces, Docker topology, auth modes, and a staged migration plan for the next 2 to 3 implementation phases.

